ECUADOR 🇪🇨 Excerpt from Eat the World NYC: There are stretches of Wyckoff Avenue, of course, that you should steer clear of these days. A combination of dangers and threats from fixed-gear bikes chained to every surface; large, apparently unshowered and unshaven men in plaid roaming everywhere, and the ever-present risk of drowning in craft beer get worse the closer you come to Flushing Avenue.  Luckily as you near Myrtle Avenue, and especially when you cross to the other side, the ubiquity of women dressed like they live in the 1980's goes down, and the chances to find excellent food goes significantly up. One such restaurant to eat well and avoid the dangers of all these other things is a small Ecuadorian nook named for the dish it features most prominently: Encebellado.  On a second visit, with an unexpectedly buzzing late afternoon crowd, a bowl of encebollado regular ($12) was tucked into and savored. The regular version of this popular soup is filled with meaty whitefish, cooked of course with onions as the name suggests. With maritime themes painted on the walls, it is easy to close your eyes and smell the Pacific Coast as if you were sitting in a seafood shack near Guayaquil.

(Translated by Google) The food is honestly good, but the restaurant is very small they cannot accommodate many people, batteries if you order coffee they give you half a cup that in case it is very small, the milk you have to wait since they give it to you apart and after ordering it a couple of times, the bolon kicks several Ecuadorian restaurants, including Barzola, who by the way became a Colombian restaurant in Jackson HTS. The owners of this restaurant are very cordial and humble so far. The onion is usually fresh, they need to be warm, the accompanying rice is cold. For breakfast it is better to make the bolon, piiilas that ends as at 11 AM. They change a lot of waitresses, except for the one that stays in the bar with take out orders. To give you the bill is another delay. But with all these mistakes that can be corrected, this restaurant is a good palate and you pay for what you eat, stop complaining about my people that here in New York the rent is already at 1,000 dollars for every 10 square feet, especially trade areas, so let's support ours >>>>>>>>  (Original) La comida sinceramente es buena, pero el restaurante es muy pequeño no pueden acomodar mucha gente, pilas si ordenas cafe te dan la mitad de una taza que por si es muy pequeña,  la leche tienes q esperar ya que te la dan aparte y despues de pedirla un par de veces, el bolon le da diez patadas a varios restaurantes Ecuatorianos, inclusive a Barzola que por cierto se volvieron en restaurante Colombiano en Jackson HTS. Los dueños de este restaurante son bien cordiales y humildes hasta el momento. El encebollado suele a estar fresco, necesitan darlo bien calientito, el arroz acompañante frio. De desayuno es mejor hacerle al bolon, piiilas que se acaba como a las 11 AM. Cambian mucho de meseras, excepto por la que se mantiene en la barra con Las  ordenes de take out. Para darte  la cuenta es otra demora. Pero con todos estos errores que pueden ser correjidos, este restaurante es de buen paladar y pagas por lo que comes, dejen de quejarse de precio mi gente que aqui en Nueva York la renta ya esta como a 1,000 dolares por cada 10 pies cuadrado, especialmente areas de comercio, asi que apoyemos lo nuestro>>>>>>>>

i am not from ecuador, but genuinely i know what a real “home cooked” meal tastes like.  the couple of experiences i have had at this glorious culinary institution have been a true joy.  service could use a bit of coaching, just as much as i do in knowing what moto is.  huh?  when moto enters my mouth however, i go to heaven twice and go back again. their food has the unforgetable grandma’s touch and the magic of authenticity.  love this place!  #food
